Doc Del, Tom is right, you are an impossible post to follow. What a story. Your writing is poetic, and the story moving.<br><br>
Yes, many cultures have incredible beauty, and yes, much of &quot;our&quot; American culture is incredibly brutal and ugly.  When I wrote of multi-culturalism, it was more in thinking with the group-speak, the need for every group it seems (at least here on the mainland) to preference their being an American, i.e. Afro-American, Hispanic-American, etc.  I think we are all just Americans, but given the political correctness that seems to be taking over certain sectors of our society, we all will have to hang several discriptive phrases on our i.d.'s....it just seems totally absurd.  <br><br>
How do native-born Hawaiian's take to all the other groups? Isn't there an anti-outsider movement?  A seperatist or native Hawaiian movement?  <br><br>
I agree, that Hawaii does seem to be the ultimate melting pot, and one in harmony and peace.  But, with all these cultural mixes, is there a Little Japan, or a Little Hmong, or Little China in the islands?  I have never been to Hawaii and truly don't know.  Or, is it that one's cultural background, like your Mr. Fujihara, was kept personal and private, and that he did not feel the need to proclaim his roots in neon signs and public neighborhoods?<br><br>
To Betty:  I will gladly &quot;get a grip&quot; if you can tell me what &quot;alias lien&quot; got all riled up over?  My second post was in reaction to her going &quot;off&quot; at me with no basis (that I was aware of). Can you explain. How did she ever decide that I did not respect her, or that &quot;respect&quot; was even an issue, or that I was a &quot;hostile stranger&quot; to her?  Stranger, yes, but how or why would I be &quot;hostile&quot; to a stranger?  Kind of an oxymoron there.  I truly am at a loss, hence my final conclusion that her over-reation had a political or secondary agenda. <br><br>
To Doc Del: You wrote: &quot;I have been to New York, San Antonio, Dallas, Chicago, and even Los Angles and the impression that I have of these places are that the only thing missing are the walls of the onclaves that everyone has made for themselves. Is this the ideal &quot;American Culture&quot; that you are touting so loudly about? Or is it the goose-stepping neo-nazi's idea of a &quot;Aryan Culture&quot; devoid of Blacks, Brown,  Yellows, or Reds?&quot;  God No.  It is not that I resent or do not want the &quot;colors&quot; of other cultures, I just want us all, ALL, (all colors,cultures, and peoples) to come together as Americans.  Not Jewish-Americans, Not Afro-Americans, Not Irish-Americans, Not Red-Neck Americans, just plain old Americans.  I guess I just see &quot;culture&quot; or &quot;race&quot; as something like religion, you do it where and when you want, but you don't push it into your neighbor's face (except for a few fundamentalist religions), and you keep it at home, and out of the public schools. Oh, before I end this, of course &quot;just because that is how it is&quot; does not make it right, and I do not support any type of racial bigotry.  I was trying to be historical correct, instead of, I guess, politically correct.  I like the ideal, but I acknowledge (unfortunately) the real.<br><br>
Does any off what I am trying to say, make sense? It seems that I am out of mental synch today, or are we playing with loaded words that have multiple meanings, and someone's secondary agenda?  Call me Barry, Call me doc, Call me confused...<br>
doc<br><br>

